fields.description:
We have multiple 'regions' within each environment.

For speed in deployment we have a Pipelines step that is manually triggered and will then deploy to all the regions in parallel, using a parallel step.

The problem with this approach is that all the deployment steps are nested within a 'parallel' and therefore BBP will not display the diff dialog showing the issues and commits that are going to be deployed.  We miss the assurance/safety that this dialog offers.

It would be great if we could have some kind of 'parallel deployment' step that would still show this diff dialog. So the requirements are:
 # Manually triggered parallel deployment to multiple 'regions' within an environment (staging and production)
 # Presentation of the 'environment diff' dialog before these deployments.
 ## we maintain all regions within an environment at the same deployment but I understand there would be complexities if these regions were out of sync.

At the moment we can 'emulate' the above by creating a 'fake environment' and we use this in the deployment step that then triggers the parallel deployment to the real environments

e.g.

 
{{<snip>}}
{{# Manually trigger deployment to a non-real first stg region, then the rest will trigger in parallel automatically.}}
{{# This is so BBP can still show us the deployment diff dialog which you lose if you parallel up all the deployments.}}
{{{}- step:{}}}{{{}name: Deploy to stg environments{}}}
{{  deployment: stg-null}}
{{  <<: *null-deploy-for-kickoff}}
{{  - parallel:}}
{{  - step:}}
{{      name: Deploy service to stg-env-1}}
{{      deployment: stg-env-1}}
{{{}      <<: *{}}}{{{}service{}}}{{{}-deploy{}}}
{{  - step:}}
{{      name: Deploy }}{{service}}{{ to stg-env-2}}
{{      deployment: stg-env-2}}
{{{}      <<: *{}}}{{{}service{}}}{{{}-deploy{}}}
{{  - step:}}
{{      name: Deploy }}{{service}}{{ to stg-env-3}}
{{      deployment: stg-env-3}}
{{{}      <<: *{}}}{{{}service{}}}{{{}-deploy{}}}
{{<etc>}}

h3. Issue Summary
* When searching on Code search for any specific string, sometimes, the search returns a json parsing error:
{code}
{
  "type": "error",
  "error": {
    "message": "Expecting value: line 1 column 1 (char 0)"
  }
}
{code}
 !code_search.png|thumbnail! 
* This issue does not affect all users, meaning one user could be facing this issue searching for code and another one might not face it;

h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Open your workspace;
 # Click on the search icon to search for code on your workspace

h3. Expected Results
* Code search should return the results of your query;

h3. Actual Results
* Code search is failing with a Json parsing issue;

h3. Workaround
* As a workaround it is possible to use our REST API to fetch this information:
{code}
$ Curl -X GET "https://api.bitbucket.org/2.0/teams/<workspace>/search/code?search_query=<query>"
{code}

h3. Issue Summary
While running test cases with testcafe, the number of test results shows double the actual number of test failures/passes.

h3. Steps to Reproduce
Tests:
Filename : testcafe/fixtures/test-fixture.js
{code:java} 
fixture("double error on bitbucket fixture").page("www.google.com");

test("Should not count error twice", async (t) => {
  await t.expect(true).eql(false);
});
{code}

Bitbucket pipelines yaml file:

{code:java}
image: testcafe/testcafe
pipelines:
  branches:
    master:
      - step:
          script:
            - npm install
            - npm ci
            - /opt/testcafe/docker/testcafe-docker.sh 'firefox:headless --no-sandbox --disable-dev-shm-usage' testcafe/fixtures/test-fixture.js -r xunit:reports/test-results/bitbucket/report.xml
{code}

Package.json:

{code:java}
{
    "scripts": {
        "test": "testcafe chrome tests/**/* -s path=results/screenshots,takeOnFails=true -S --video results/videos --reporter nunit3:report.xml"
    },
    "devDependencies": {
        "testcafe": "^1.14.0",
        "testcafe-reporter-nunit3": "^3.0.0",
        "@ffmpeg-installer/ffmpeg": "^1.0.20"
    }
}
{code}

h3. Expected Results

{code:java}
1 / 1 tests failed
{code}

h3. Actual Results
{code:java}
2 / 1 tests failed
{code}


h3. Workaround

No workaround at the moment.

h3. Issue Summary

While using the Pull Request API call endpoint it is not possible to set pagelen > 50
eg.
{code}
https://api.bitbucket.org/2.0/repositories/<owner>/<repository>/pullrequests/?pagelen=51
{code}

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Run a API call for the Pull Requeest endpoint
#* {code}
https://api.bitbucket.org/2.0/repositories/<owner>/<repository>/pullrequests/?pagelen=51
{code}


h3. Expected Results

As mentioned on the documentation, get the result of < 50 Pull Requests

h3. Actual Results

{code}
{
  "type": "error",
  "error": {
    "message": "Invalid pagelen"
  }
}
{code}

h3. Workaround

Use the API call with the pagelen number >= 50
eg.
{code}
https://api.bitbucket.org/2.0/repositories/<owner>/<repository>/pullrequests/?pagelen=50
{code}

I think it would make more sense to move the trigger command to the pipeline section rather than having it associated with a step. Consider the following scenario, for my codebase, I would like to automatically create a docker container for my application only when built off the main branch, for any other branch, I would like that to be a manual click.

Currently, I would have to do this like so:
{color:#000000}- {color}{color:#008080}step{color}{color:#000000}: &Deliver-docker-step-manual{color}
{color:#008080} services{color}{color:#000000}:{color}
{color:#000000} - {color}{color:#0451a5}docker{color}
{color:#008080} name{color}{color:#000000}: {color}{color:#0451a5}Deliver - Docker{color}
{color:#008080} script{color}{color:#000000}:{color}
{color:#000000} - {color}{color:#0451a5}docker build -f ./Dockerfile -t $DOCKER_IMAGE_BASE:$BUILD_VER -t $DOCKER_IMAGE_BASE:$LATEST_TAG --build-arg APP_VERSION=$BUILD_VER --build-arg APP_PORT=8080 .{color}
{color:#0451a5} trigger: manual{color}
 
{color:#000000}- {color}{color:#008080}step{color}{color:#000000}: &Deliver-docker-step-auto{color}
{color:#008080} services{color}{color:#000000}:{color}
{color:#000000} - {color}{color:#0451a5}docker{color}
{color:#008080} name{color}{color:#000000}: {color}{color:#0451a5}Deliver - Docker{color}
{color:#008080} script{color}{color:#000000}:{color}
{color:#000000} - {color}{color:#0451a5}docker build -f ./Dockerfile -t $DOCKER_IMAGE_BASE:$BUILD_VER -t $DOCKER_IMAGE_BASE:$LATEST_TAG --build-arg APP_VERSION=$BUILD_VER --build-arg APP_PORT=8080 .{color}
 
{color:#008080}branches{color}{color:#000000}:{color}
{color:#000000} default:{color}
{color:#000000} - step: *Deliver-docker-step-manual{color}
{color:#008080} main{color}{color:#000000}:{color}
{color:#000000} - {color}{color:#008080}step{color}{color:#000000}: *Deliver-docker-step-auto{color}
 
{color:#000000}{color:#000000}Lots of redundancy. Imagine that over dozens of different steps. Preferably, I think it would make more sense to do something like:

{color}{color}
{color:#000000}- {color}{color:#008080}step{color}{color:#000000}: &Deliver-docker-step{color}
{color:#008080} services{color}{color:#000000}:{color}
{color:#000000} - {color}{color:#0451a5}docker{color}
{color:#008080} name{color}{color:#000000}: {color}{color:#0451a5}Deliver - Docker{color}
{color:#008080} script{color}{color:#000000}:{color}
{color:#000000} - {color}{color:#0451a5}docker build -f ./Dockerfile -t $DOCKER_IMAGE_BASE:$BUILD_VER -t $DOCKER_IMAGE_BASE:$LATEST_TAG --build-arg APP_VERSION=$BUILD_VER --build-arg APP_PORT=8080 .
{color}
{color:#008080}branches{color}{color:#000000}:{color}
{color:#000000} default:{color}
{color:#000000} - step: *Deliver-docker-step{color}
{color:#000000} - trigger: manual{color}
{color:#008080} main{color}{color:#000000}:{color}
{color:#000000} - {color}{color:#008080}step{color}{color:#000000}: *Deliver-docker-step{color}
{color:#000000}
Where auto-deploy in this case would be the default (and thus used by main). That way I only need to define my step a single time, but I can have it run both manually or automatically as needed for a given pipeline.{color}

h3. Issue Summary

When you open a Pull request through the commit button option, the default description is not populated. 
h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Go to your source page and open the file you want to edit;
 # Edit the file;
 # Click on Merge;
 # Select the option to create a Pull Request.

h3. Expected Results

The default description template should display on the "description" option
h3. Actual Results

The commit message display instead. 
h3. Workaround

As a workaround you can:
 * Go to your source page and open the file you want to edit;
 * Edit the file;
 * Click on Merge whiteout selecting to create a PR;
 * Go to the PR tab;
 * Click on "Create a Pull Request";
 * The PR default description will display.
